CI/CD Pipeline & EKS Deployment — WDTech Property Valuation API

Step 1: What We Built Locally
"To start, I built a Property Valuation API using FastAPI and Python. The API takes property details like address, bedrooms, bathrooms, square footage, location score, and year built — and returns an estimated property value in USD.
I containerized it using Docker with this Dockerfile:
dockerfileFROM python:3.11-alpine

WORKDIR /app

COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

COPY . .

EXPOSE 8000

CMD ["uvicorn", "app.main:app", "--host", "0.0.0.0", "--port", "8000"]
I then built and tagged the image using semantic versioning:
powershelldocker build -t wdtech-property-valuation:1.0.0 .
And ran it locally:
powershelldocker run -d -p 8000:8000 --name wdtech-valuation-dev wdtech-property-valuation:1.0.0
The API was accessible at http://localhost:8000/docs and returned a 200 OK with an estimated property value."

Step 2: Environment Variables
"One of the key requirements was making the API configurable without changing the code. I achieved this using environment variables.
The API reads BASE_PRICE_PER_SQFT from the environment:
pythonBASE_PRICE_PER_SQFT = float(os.getenv("BASE_PRICE_PER_SQFT", "150"))
```

I created a `.env` file:
```
BASE_PRICE_PER_SQFT=200
APP_ENV=production
And injected it into the container at runtime:
powershelldocker run -d -p 8000:8000 --env-file .env --name wdtech-valuation-dev wdtech-property-valuation:1.0.0
I verified the variable was applied:
powershelldocker exec wdtech-valuation-dev env | findstr BASE_PRICE_PER_SQFT
# OUTPUT: BASE_PRICE_PER_SQFT=200
This means different environments — dev, staging, production — can all use the same Docker image but with different configurations. No code changes needed."

Step 3: Designing the CI Pipeline
"Now that the app works locally, the next step is automating the build and deployment process using a GitLab CI/CD pipeline.
The pipeline has 3 stages — build, push, and deploy — triggered automatically whenever a new version tag is pushed to GitLab."
.gitlab-ci.yml:
yamlstages:
  - build
  - push
  - deploy

variables:
  IMAGE_TAG: $CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_TAG

build:
  stage: build
  script:
    - docker build -t $IMAGE_TAG .
  only:
    - tags

push:
  stage: push
  script:
    - docker login -u $CI_REGISTRY_USER -p $CI_REGISTRY_PASSWORD $CI_REGISTRY
    - docker push $IMAGE_TAG
  only:
    - tags

deploy:
  stage: deploy
  script:
    - aws eks update-kubeconfig --name wdtech-cluster --region us-east-1
    - kubectl set image deployment/wdtech-property-valuation wdtech-property-valuation=$IMAGE_TAG
  only:
    - tags
"Let me walk through each stage:
Build stage — GitLab runner picks up the code and runs docker build, producing the same image I built locally — wdtech-property-valuation:1.0.0. The $CI_COMMIT_TAG variable ensures the image is tagged with the exact release version.
Push stage — The image is pushed to the GitLab Container Registry using built-in GitLab variables $CI_REGISTRY_USER, $CI_REGISTRY_PASSWORD, and $CI_REGISTRY. No hardcoded credentials anywhere — GitLab manages this securely.
Deploy stage — This is where EKS comes in. aws eks update-kubeconfig connects to our AWS EKS cluster, and kubectl set image tells Kubernetes to roll out the new version of the container across all running pods."

Step 4: How EKS Runs the Container
"In EKS, the API runs as a Kubernetes Deployment. This is the equivalent of our docker run command locally, but managed by Kubernetes at scale:
yamlapiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: wdtech-property-valuation
spec:
  replicas: 2
  template:
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: wdtech-property-valuation
          image: registry.gitlab.com/wdtech/wdtech-property-valuation:1.0.0
          ports:
            - containerPort: 8000
          env:
            - name: BASE_PRICE_PER_SQFT
              value: "200"
            - name: APP_ENV
              value: "production"
```

The `replicas: 2` means Kubernetes runs **2 instances** of the container simultaneously — so if one pod goes down, the other keeps serving requests. The environment variables we tested locally with `--env-file .env` are defined here directly in the deployment manifest."

